{{Infobox language |name=Bishuo |states=[[Cameroon]] |extinct=ca. 2000 |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo languages|Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Benue–Congo languages|Benue–Congo]] |fam4=[[Southern Bantoid]] |fam5=[[Beboid languages|Beboid]]? |fam6=[[Furu languages|Furu]] |iso3=bwh |glotto=bish1246 |glottorefname=Bishuo }}
The '''Bishuo language''' is an extinct or nearly extinct [[Furu languages|Furu language]] of [[Cameroon]]. It was spoken in the [[North West Province]], [[Menchum|Menchum Department]], Furu-Awa Subdivision, Ntjieka, Furu-Turuwa and the Furu-Sambari villages. It was related to [[Bikya language]]. It was reported by Breton 1986 that the [[Bishuo people]] had shifted to [[Jukun Takum language|Jukun]], with apparently only one remaining person, over 60 years old, who knew any Bishuo.
